1. **FileResourceManager** (core/src/main/java/io/undertow/server/handlers/resource/FileResourceManager.java): The `getResource()` method at line 80 constructs a `File` object from user-controlled HTTP path input (via `exchange.getRelativePath()` in ResourceHandler). The security check at line 94 only verifies `file.getCanonicalFile().getName().equals(file.getName())` - this only checks case-sensitivity of the filename component, NOT that the resolved canonical path is contained within the base directory. An attacker can use `../../etc/passwd` to escape the base directory. There is NO containment check (no startsWith on canonical path vs base).

2. **ClassPathResourceManager** (core/src/main/java/io/undertow/server/handlers/resource/ClassPathResourceManager.java): The `getResource()` method at line 42 strips the leading slash, prepends a prefix, then passes directly to `classLoader.getResource()` without any check for `..` sequences. An attacker can traverse outside the configured classpath prefix using paths like `../../sensitive-resource`.

Both vulnerabilities are directly reachable from HTTP request paths via ResourceHandler.java line 131 which calls `resourceManager.getResource(exchange.getRelativePath())` with no path sanitization.
